ce:section.ce:para:
The default CNN backbone used is a ten-layer ResNet-like architecture (ResNet-10). 40 We evaluated alternative models, including ResNet, ShuffleNet, 41 and EfficientNet, 42 of varying sizes to demonstrate the advantages of ResNet-10. The experimental results indicate that within the same CNN architecture, an increase in model parameters generally leads to improved estimation accuracy (see Figure 6 and Table S7). However, unlike the standard 2D images commonly used in computer vision tasks, the scales of transformed images in this study input to backbones are smaller (
h , w ≤ 32
), which limits the ability of deeper layers to learn representation, ultimately affecting model performance. Therefore, rather than simply increasing the scale, designing a model of appropriate architecture is crucial for balancing estimation accuracy with computational resource requirements. Thus, although EfficientNet can achieve better accuracy on AOC15, ResNet-10 was still used as the CNN backbone because of its efficiency in the experiments.
